ts":[{"name":"Lonon","meanings":["English: probably a variant of   London  . This surname is very rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Lundon","meanings":["English: variant of   London  ."]}]},{"name":"Eleanor","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ellenor","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor  , the result of blending with   Ellen ."]},{"name":"Elenor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]},{"name":"Elinor","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":71,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705202,"age":80,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705205,"age":91,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705206,"age":93,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Eleanor London was born in 1478, in England. She married William Rymer about 1500, in Lambeth, London, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"1478–":"1478–Surnud","1475–1550":"1475–1550","1500–1585":"1500–1585","1478–Female":"1478–Surnud","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1478":"1478","1500":"1500","1585":"1585","1475":"1475","1550":"1550","about 1500":"umbes 1500","1571":"1571","1549":"1549","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Lambeth, London, England, United Kingdom":"Lambeth, London, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England"},"fi":{"1478–":"1478–Kuollut","1475–1550":"1475–1550","1500–1585":"1500–1585","1478–Female":"1478–Kuollut","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1478":"1478","1500":"1500","1585":"1585","1475":"1475","1550":"1550","about 1500":"noin 1500","1571":"1571","1549":"1549","London, Middlesex, England":"London, Middlesex, England","Lambeth, London, England, U